<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do I size a chimney flue?", answer: "The required flue cross-section area depends on the appliance type and BTU output. Wood stoves and fireplaces need about 1 sq in of flue area per 30,000 BTU/hr. Gas appliances with Category I draft hoods need about 1 sq in per 75,000 BTU/hr. Oil appliances need 1 sq in per 40,000 BTU/hr. Divide the BTU by the appropriate factor to get the required area." },
  { question: "How tall does a chimney need to be?", answer: "NFPA 211 requires chimneys to extend at least 3 feet above the highest point where they pass through the roof, and at least 2 feet higher than any part of the roof within 10 feet horizontally. For a wood stove, the total chimney height should be at least 15 feet from the flue collar to the cap for adequate draft. Gas appliances can work with shorter chimneys (5-10 ft) because they produce lower flue gas temperatures." },
  { question: "What is the 3-2-10 rule?", answer: "The universal chimney height rule: the chimney must be at least 3 ft above where it exits the roof AND at least 2 ft higher than anything within 10 ft horizontally. This prevents downdraft, wind-caused backdraft, and smoke spillage onto the roof. Measure from the highest point of the roof penetration, not the average roof height." },
  { question: "Can a chimney be oversized?", answer: "Yes — an oversized flue cools exhaust gases too much, causing condensation, creosote buildup in wood systems, and reduced draft. For wood burning, never exceed 3× the required flue area. Modern EPA-certified stoves often specify a 6 inch flue regardless of BTU output because they are designed around that size. Always follow the stove manufacturer's listed flue size if specified." },
  { question: "Does chimney height affect draft?", answer: "Yes, significantly. Draft is driven by the temperature difference between the flue gases and outside air multiplied by the chimney height. A 15 ft chimney has 50% more draft than a 10 ft chimney at the same temperature. If your appliance is puffing smoke into the room, the first fix is usually to lengthen the chimney." }
]) %>

